article.headline: Kings improve to 22-3 at Arco
article.linkText: Kings beat Sonics for 2nd time in 4 days
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Anthony Peeler's superb defense kept Ray Allen from beating the Sacramento Kings in the second half. Peeler had 14 points, six rebounds and five assists in a season-high 32 minutes and the Kings won their fourth straight game, 117-101 over the Seattle SuperSonics on Tuesday night. "We just tried to come in and play great defense and make Ray work for his buckets," Peeler said. "And when my shot comes, I'm going to take it." Allen had 23 points, five rebounds and five assists after being named to the All-Star team earlier in the day for the fourth time in his career -- but he was held to eight points after halftime. "He turned things around," Sacramento center Vlade Divac said of Peeler, a 6-foot-4 reserve guard. Brad Miller scored 14 of his 25 points in the third quarter for the Western Conference-leading Kings, who opened a three-game homestand with an inspired second half to beat the Sonics for the second time in four days. Sacramento has a half-game lead over Minnesota in the conference standings after the Timberwolves defeated the Orlando Magic on Tuesday. Peja Stojakovic had 26 points as the Kings improved to 22-3 this season at Arco Arena. Rashard Lewis led Seattle with 25 points. "I thought we gave all we had in that first half," said Sonics coach Nate McMillan, whose team seemed sluggish at times after playing Chicago at home Monday night. "In the third quarter, they came out much more aggressive." The 7-foot Miller, selected to his second All-Star team along with Stojakovic, also had four rebounds and two assists in the Kings' decisive 33-point third quarter. He finished with 15 boards, five assists, a steal and a block. He did miss a wide-open dunk late in the game, but laughed it off. Miller had planned to spend the All-Star break ice fishing and riding his four-wheeler. "I could care less about the recognition," he said. "It has been overwhelming since I got out here. I was hoping to kind of blend in a little bit better. But you take the good with the bad." Lewis made his first six shots, including three from 3-point range as the Sonics jumped to an early lead. He had back-to-back 3s midway through the second quarter during a stretch when Seattle hit three straight from long range. Miller, Stojakovic and Allen were selected as reserves for the Western Conference All-Star team for the Feb. 15 game in Los Angeles. The Kings just returned from a season-long, six-game road trip, which included a 110-103 win Saturday night in Seattle. Seattle's Antonio Daniels, who came in averaging 16.6 points in his last five games, was held to 13 after going off for a career-high 30 against Sacramento on Saturday. But he passed for a career-high 14 assists. Bobby Jackson added 16 points and six rebounds off the bench for Sacramento, while Seattle reserve Vladimir Radmanovic scored 19. Stojakovic's 3 with 5:32 left in the third tied the game at 70, and the Kings followed by hitting two more from long range, one by Peeler and the other by Mike Bibby that gave Sacramento a 76-71 lead. The Kings took an 89-81 lead into the fourth and quickly turned the game into a blowout. "We missed shots we normally make and we turned the ball over more," Daniels said. "When you do that, they'll make you pay." Allen and Lewis each had 15 of their points in the first half as Seattle took a 61-56 lead at the break. The Kings missed several shots from close range and were short on their jumpers in the first quarter, falling behind 34-26. Sacramento still shot 52.4 percent in the period to Seattle's 59.1, but the Sonics went hard to the boards for a 12-6 rebounding edge. The Kings outrebounded the Sonics 43-35 overall.

Game notes
Allen figured he'd be a long shot to make the All-Star team after missing the first 25 games this season with a hurt right ankle. That's why when he got word Tuesday that he'd earned a spot on the team for the fourth time in his career, he had a little fun when his mother called. "My mom called and said, 'Did you make it?" Allen said before the Sonics played the Sacramento Kings on Tuesday night. "I said no. She said, 'I don't care about anybody else in the NBA. You're still an All-Star.' I said, 'Mom, I made it!' and she screamed." ... Sacramento has won the season series with Seattle for two straight seasons after splitting their meetings the previous four years. ... Divac had a season-high 11 assists. ... Miller had his 23rd double-double.
